\begin{slide}
\section{Recap}

\begin{PauseHighLight}
  \begin{itemize}
  \item Recall the Fisher-Wright model looks at how a mutant allele
    at a single locus would take over the population\pause
  \item For finite populations this is a stochastic process\pause
  \item We can simulate this happening (each simulation will give us a
    different result)\pause
  \item We can also compute $\bm{p}(t) = \left(\strut p_0(t),\,
      p_1(t),\, \ldots,\, p_P(t) \right)$ telling us the probability of
    $n$ mutants at time $t$ using a Markov chain analysis\pause
  \item Unfortunately, we can only do this for small populations\pause
  \end{itemize}
\end{PauseHighLight}

\end{slide}

%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%% Next Slide %%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

\begin{slide}
\section{Stochasticity in Biology}

\begin{PauseHighLight}
  \begin{itemize}
  \item By its very nature dynamics in biology is very random\pause
  \item Sometimes this doesn't matter (we can ignore the
    randomness)\pause
  \item But sometimes this randomness is an essential part of
    nature\pause
  \item This is particularly true when the dynamics depends on rare
    events that might not happen\pause
  \item This is true in population genetics, but also in gene regulation
    which we explore later in the course\pause
  \end{itemize}
\end{PauseHighLight}

\end{slide}

%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%% Next Slide %%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

\begin{slide}
\section{Language of Random Dynamics}

\begin{PauseHighLight}
  \begin{itemize}
  \item When the underlying dynamics involve small random kicks then we
    can develop a calculus known as \emph{stochastic differential
      equation}\pause
  \item This is used across the sciences\pause
  \item It was originally used to describe physical diffusion\pause
  \item It is used, for example, in describing fluctuations in
    finance\pause
  \end{itemize}
\end{PauseHighLight}

\end{slide}


